        <h2>The Real Culprit: Your Cellular Energy System is Failing</h2>

        <p>Here's what's actually happening inside your body at 2 PM:</p>

        <p>Your cells have been working hard all morning, producing energy through tiny structures called <strong>mitochondria</strong>. But by mid-afternoon, these cellular power plants start running out of steam.</p>

        <p>It's not about food or coffee‚Äîit's about <strong>your cells' ability to produce energy at the molecular level</strong>.</p>

        <div class="scientific-box">
            <h3>üî¨ The Science of Afternoon Energy Decline</h3>
            <p><strong>Your mitochondria need a molecule called NAD to produce energy.</strong> Research shows that NAD levels naturally fluctuate throughout the day.</p>
            <p>By early afternoon, your NAD stores are depleted from morning activities. Without adequate NAD, your mitochondria can't produce ATP (cellular energy) efficiently.</p>
            <p>This is why you feel tired regardless of what you eat or how much coffee you drink‚Äîthe problem is at the cellular level.</p>
        </div>

