        <h2>Why Coffee Makes It Worse (The Vicious Cycle)</h2>

        <p>When you crash at 2 PM, your first instinct is to reach for coffee. But here's the problem:</p>

        <p><strong>Coffee doesn't fix cellular energy production‚Äîit just masks the problem.</strong> Caffeine blocks adenosine receptors in your brain, making you feel temporarily alert. But your mitochondria are still struggling to produce energy.</p>

        <p>Worse yet, afternoon caffeine disrupts your sleep, leading to deeper fatigue the next day. It's a vicious cycle that gets worse over time.</p>

        <blockquote>
            "Caffeine is like putting a band-aid on a broken engine. You might feel better temporarily, but the underlying problem gets worse." - Dr. Matthew Walker, Sleep Scientist
        </blockquote>

        <h2>The NAD Solution: Fixing Energy at the Source</h2>

        <p>The breakthrough discovery is this: <strong>When you restore NAD levels, the afternoon crash disappears.</strong></p>

        <p>NAD (Nicotinamide Adenine Dinucleotide) is your body's master energy molecule. Every cell needs it to produce energy. When NAD levels drop, energy production plummets.</p>

        <div class="truth-box">
            <h3>‚úÖ What Happens When You Restore NAD Levels:</h3>
